Summer Institute Social Security Panel Focuses
on Recent Trends in Fertility in the United States

   The U.S. fertility rate — an important driver of the long-term
   financial health of the Social Security system — has trended downward
   since the 1960s, and fallen noticeably in the last decade. Academic
   researchers joined experts from the Social Security Administration to
   discuss these trends and their implications at the 2019 NBER Summer
   Institute. The panel was introduced by NBER President James Poterba.
   View videos of the presentations
     __________________________________________________________________

New NBER Research

   25 September 2019

Benefits of Early Exposure to Professional Work

   Engineering majors exposed to professional work early in their college
   careers take more engineering courses and are more likely to switch to
   higher-income subfields within engineering, a field experiment by Kevin
   J. Boudreau and Matt Marx shows. The effects were most pronounced for
   lower-income students.
   ( ...more... )

   24 September 2019

U.S. Monetary Policy and International Bond Markets

   Analyzing data starting in the early 1990s, Simon Gilchrist, Vivian
   Yue, and Egon Zakrajšek find that yields on dollar-denominated
   sovereign debt are highly responsive to unanticipated changes in the
   stance of U.S. monetary policy, regardless of whether those changes
   represent conventional or unconventional policies.
   ( ...more... )

   23 September 2019

The Failure of Free Entry

   Regulations drive down the entry and growth of small firms relative to
   large ones in the United States, particularly in industries with high
   lobbying expenditures, Germán Gutiérrez and Thomas Philippon show.
   ( ...more... )

