  The NBER Digest

Examination of Returns to U.S. Government Programs
Shows Investment in Low-Income Children Most Beneficial

   [w26144.jpg]

   U.S. government programs that provide early childhood health
   interventions reduce subsequent Medicaid-financed health care needs and
   increase future earnings and tax payments, improving government
   finances in the long run, research featured in the September edition of
   The NBER Digest shows. Other studies in this edition of the free,
   monthly Digest document reduction in the percentage of black teachers
   in Southern schools that desegregated, explore the influence of
   early-career research experience, show that borrowers who are aware of
   their FICO scores are less likely to be overdue on loan payments, gauge
   the impacts of R&D tax credits, and explore the contemporary relevance
   of the Phillips curve.
   Read online Download the PDF
     __________________________________________________________________

Bulletin on Health

Winter Deaths Averted by Lower Home Heating Prices

   [w25681.jpg]
   The summer issue of the Bulletin on Health features a study of the
   effects of heating costs on deaths from health conditions that are
   worsened by cold weather. Researchers find that households reduce their
   home energy use when prices increase, but not so much as to fully
   offset the price increase, so they are still exposed to higher energy
   bills. They demonstrate that higher heating prices also increase
   mortality rates, especially for cardiovascular and respiratory causes
   of death, and in lower-income counties. Their estimates imply that the
   lowered price of heating due to shale natural gas production and other
   factors in the late 2000s averted 11,000 winter deaths per year in
   areas that relied on this heating energy source. Also featured in the
   summer issue of the Bulletin on Health are studies of the effects of
   California’s change in vaccine laws on vaccination and medical
   exemption rates, and the distributional impact of penicillin’s
   introduction on mortality in Italy following World War II.
   Read online
     __________________________________________________________________

NBER's Entrepreneurship Research Boot Camp
Explores Dynamics of Firm Creation and Innovation

   For the 12th year, leading researchers and graduate students interested
   in entrepreneurship met for an intensive week of study at NBER
   headquarters in Cambridge, MA, sponsored by the Ewing Marion Kauffman
   Foundation.
     __________________________________________________________________

  Bulletin on Retirement and Disability

The Insurance and Liquidity Value
of Social Security Survivors Benefits?

   [w25586.jpg]

   In 2015, the Social Security program paid over $95 billion in survivors
   benefits to 4.2 million surviving spouses. Research that is the first
   to explore the protective role of survivors benefit receipt against the
   short-run financial consequences of a spousal death finds that
   attaining benefit eligibility is associated with a 34-percentage point
   increase in Social Security receipt and a 3.1-percentage point decline
   in labor force participation. Also summarized in this first issue of
   the free Bulletin on Retirement and Disability: research that estimates
   the total value of Great Recession-induced disability insurance (DI)
   awards and a study of the effects of DI awards on the financial
   outcomes of applicants.

   Read online
     __________________________________________________________________

